TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Supply-Side Effects of Monetary Policy
AU  - Baqaee, David R.
AU  - Farhi, Emmanuel
AU  - Sangani, Kunal
Y1  - 2023/08/16
PY  - 2023
DA  - 2024/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/727287
DO  - 10.1086/727287
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 1065
EP  - 1112
VL  - 132
IS  - 4
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - We propose a supply-side channel for the transmission of monetary policy. We show that when high-markup firms have lower pass-throughs than low-markup firms, then positive demand shocks, such as monetary expansions, alleviate cross-sectional misallocation by reallocating resources to high-markup firms. Consequently, positive ?demand shocks? are accompanied by endogenous positive ?supply shocks? that raise productivity and lower inflation. We derive a tractable, four-equation model where monetary shocks generate hump-shaped productivity responses. In our calibration, the supply-side effect amplifies the total impact of monetary shocks on output by about 70%. We provide empirical evidence validating our model?s predictions using identified monetary shocks.
AB  - We propose a supply-side channel for the transmission of monetary policy. We show that when high-markup firms have lower pass-throughs than low-markup firms, then positive demand shocks, such as monetary expansions, alleviate cross-sectional misallocation by reallocating resources to high-markup firms. Consequently, positive ?demand shocks? are accompanied by endogenous positive ?supply shocks? that raise productivity and lower inflation. We derive a tractable, four-equation model where monetary shocks generate hump-shaped productivity responses. In our calibration, the supply-side effect amplifies the total impact of monetary shocks on output by about 70%. We provide empirical evidence validating our model?s predictions using identified monetary shocks.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/727287
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/727287
Y2  - 2024/10/27
