TY  - JOUR
T1  - A Theory of Stock Exchange Competition and Innovation: Will the Market Fix the Market?
AU  - Budish, Eric
AU  - Lee, Robin S.
AU  - Shim, John J.
Y1  - 2023/08/16
PY  - 2023
DA  - 2024/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/727284
DO  - 10.1086/727284
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 1209
EP  - 1246
VL  - 132
IS  - 4
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - Will stock exchanges innovate to address latency arbitrage and the arms race for speed? This paper models how exchanges compete in the modern electronic era and how this shapes incentives for market-design innovation. In the status quo, exchange trading fees are competitive, but exchanges earn economic rents from selling speed. These rents create a wedge between private and social incentives to innovate and support the persistence of an inefficient market design in equilibrium of a market-design adoption game. We discuss implications for policy and insights for the literatures on market design, innovation, and platforms.
AB  - Will stock exchanges innovate to address latency arbitrage and the arms race for speed? This paper models how exchanges compete in the modern electronic era and how this shapes incentives for market-design innovation. In the status quo, exchange trading fees are competitive, but exchanges earn economic rents from selling speed. These rents create a wedge between private and social incentives to innovate and support the persistence of an inefficient market design in equilibrium of a market-design adoption game. We discuss implications for policy and insights for the literatures on market design, innovation, and platforms.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/727284
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/727284
Y2  - 2024/10/27
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Mediated Collusion
AU  - Ortner, Juan
AU  - Sugaya, Takuo
AU  - Wolitzky, Alexander
Y1  - 2023/09/06
PY  - 2023
DA  - 2024/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/727710
DO  - 10.1086/727710
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 1247
EP  - 1289
VL  - 132
IS  - 4
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - Cartels and bidding rings are often facilitated by intermediaries, who recommend prices/bids to firms and can impose penalties (such as reverting to competitive behavior in future interactions) if these recommendations are not followed. Motivated by such cases, we study correlated equilibria in first-price procurement auctions with complete information, where bidders who disobey their recommendations are penalized. Cartel-optimal profit is greater when more information about submitted bids is disclosed at auction and when the maximum penalty is larger. When only the winner?s identity is disclosed (or the winner?s identity and bid), cartels do not benefit from mediation. Our main result characterizes the cartel-optimal equilibrium with two symmetric bidders when both bids are disclosed. The optimal equilibrium involves extensive randomization and displays tied bids and high winning bids with positive probability, even when the maximum penalty is very small. The stationary mediation schemes we consider are always more profitable for the cartel than bid rotation.
AB  - Cartels and bidding rings are often facilitated by intermediaries, who recommend prices/bids to firms and can impose penalties (such as reverting to competitive behavior in future interactions) if these recommendations are not followed. Motivated by such cases, we study correlated equilibria in first-price procurement auctions with complete information, where bidders who disobey their recommendations are penalized. Cartel-optimal profit is greater when more information about submitted bids is disclosed at auction and when the maximum penalty is larger. When only the winner?s identity is disclosed (or the winner?s identity and bid), cartels do not benefit from mediation. Our main result characterizes the cartel-optimal equilibrium with two symmetric bidders when both bids are disclosed. The optimal equilibrium involves extensive randomization and displays tied bids and high winning bids with positive probability, even when the maximum penalty is very small. The stationary mediation schemes we consider are always more profitable for the cartel than bid rotation.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/727710
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/727710
Y2  - 2024/10/27
